{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2017}} '''Arlene "A. J." Delgado''' is a former [[Mediaite]] [[columnist]] who joined the [[Donald Trump presidential campaign, 2016|Donald Trump presidential campaign]] in September 2016.<ref name="Mediaite 13.9.16">{{cite news|last1=Staff|title=Former Mediaite Columnist A.J. Delgado Joins Trump Campaign|url=http://www.mediaite.com/online/former-mediaite-columnist-a-j-delgado-joins-trump-campaign/|accessdate=September 14, 2016|publisher=Mediaite|date=September 13, 2016}}</ref> She is a [[Harvard Law]] graduate who practiced law in [[New York City]].
== Early life == The child of [[Cubans|Cuban]] immigrants to the United States, Delgado is a native [[Spanish language|Spanish]] speaker.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://about.me/ajdelgado|title=A. J. Delgado|website=about.me|accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref> Her father was a bus driver; her mother worked in a factory. Delgado spoke only Spanish until [[kindergarten]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dailycaller.com/2016/07/18/this-female-hispanic-lawyer-is-campaigning-for-donald-trump/|title=This Female Hispanic Lawyer Is Campaigning For Donald Trump|website=The Daily Caller|access-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref>
== Career == Delgado's writings have been published in ''[[The American Conservative]]'', ''[[National Review]]'', ''[[The Miami Herald]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'', ''[[Breitbart]]'', ''[[The Daily Caller]]'', and [[Fox News]]. She appears regularly on ''[[Hannity]]''. She [[Self-publishing|self-published]] her book ''Hip To Be Square: Why It's Cool To Be A Conservative'' in 2012. Delgado has written about why [[Latinos]] should vote for Trump in ''[[The Washington Post]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/posteverything/wp/2016/08/22/why-latinos-should-vote-for-trump/|title=Why Latinos should vote for Trump|website=Washington Post|access-date=September 14, 2016}}</ref> On television, Delgado has regularly defended Trump from [[Donald Trump sexual misconduct allegations|numerous allegations of sexual harassment]]. On [[MSNBC]] with [[Brian Williams]] on October 12, 2016, Delgado called the claims of women who accused Trump of assault "mind boggling" and "dubious".<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[NY Magazine]]| url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2016/10/trump-camp-calls-assault-claims-absurd-questions-accusers.html|title=Trump Campaign Calls Sexual-Assault Allegations ‘Absurd,’ Surrogates Try to Discredit Accusers|date=October 13, 2016|first=Margaret|last=Hartmann}}</ref>
After the election, she joined [[Presidential transition of Donald Trump|Donald Trump's transition team]] as a campaign advisor.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/388716-ex-trump-campaign-adviser-rips-claims-of-spy-in-campaign-its|title=Ex-Trump campaign adviser rips claims of spy in campaign: It's 'embarrassing'|last=Thomsen|first=Jacqueline|date=2018-05-21|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en}}</ref> She did not join the [[Donald Trump Administration|administration]] after she found out she was [[pregnant]]: The baby's father is fellow Trump [[campaign staffer]] [[Jason Miller (communications strategist)|Jason Miller]]. According to Delgado, Miller told her that he was separated from his wife. He broke off the relationship soon after finding out that Delgado was pregnant. Delgado gave birth in July 2017 to a boy she named William.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[The Atlantic]]|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/from-trump-aide-to-single-mom/536892/|title=From Trump Aide to Single Mom|first=McKay|last=Coppins|authorlink=McKay Coppins|date=August 2017}}</ref>
In May 2018, Delgado described claims made by Trump that the FBI put a spy inside the Trump 2016 campaign to frame him as "embarrassing".<ref name=":0" /> She tweeted, "Are we really going w this?? That Obama put a spy inside the Trump campaign, to frame Trump? Srsly? Not sure if it’s IQ, ethics, or simple common sense but I cant. This is embarrassing."<ref name=":0" />
