'''Simon Loueckhote''' (born May 7, 1957) is a former member of the [[Senate of France]], representing the island of [[New Caledonia]].  He is a member of the [[Union for a Popular Movement]].

Loueckhote served as the sole member from New Caledonia to the French Senate from 1992 until 2011.<ref name=rnzi>{{cite news|first=|last=|title=New Caledonia to elect two French senators|url=http://www.rnzi.com/pages/news.php?op=read&id=63318 |work=[[Radio New Zealand International]] |publisher= |date=2011-08-23|accessdate=2011-09-24}}</ref> Loueckhote announced in September 2011 that he would not seek re-election to the Senate<ref name=rnzi/> after the [[Union for a Popular Movement]] political party threw its support to two other candidates, [[Pierre Frogier]] and [[Hilarion Vendegou]], in June.<ref name=rnzi/>

In 2011, New Caledonia's representation in the Senate of France was increased to two members as part of the Senate's enlargement.<ref name=rnzi/> An [[electoral college]] held on September 24, 2011, will elect the two new Senators, who will succeed Loueckhote.<ref name=rnzi/>

